  "preview": "Conversation on April 1: — When is your release? — April 15. Conversation on May 1: — When is your release? — May 15. — But it was supposed to be April 15 — When we tried to release, we discovered tha",
  "text": "Conversation on April 1:\n— 𝘞𝘩𝘦𝘯 𝘪𝘴 𝘺𝘰𝘶𝘳 𝘳𝘦𝘭𝘦𝘢𝘴𝘦?\n— 𝘈𝘱𝘳𝘪𝘭 15.\n\nConversation on May 1:\n— 𝘞𝘩𝘦𝘯 𝘪𝘴 𝘺𝘰𝘶𝘳 𝘳𝘦𝘭𝘦𝘢𝘴𝘦?\n— 𝘔𝘢𝘺 15.\n— 𝘉𝘶𝘵 𝘪𝘵 𝘸𝘢𝘴 𝘴𝘶𝘱𝘱𝘰𝘴𝘦𝘥 𝘵𝘰 𝘣𝘦 𝘈𝘱𝘳𝘪𝘭 15 🤔\n— 𝘞𝘩𝘦𝘯 𝘸𝘦 𝘵𝘳𝘪𝘦𝘥 𝘵𝘰 𝘳𝘦𝘭𝘦𝘢𝘴𝘦, 𝘸𝘦 𝘥𝘪𝘴𝘤𝘰𝘷𝘦𝘳𝘦𝘥 𝘵𝘩𝘢𝘵 𝘰𝘶𝘳 𝘴𝘰𝘭𝘶𝘵𝘪𝘰𝘯 𝘤𝘰𝘶𝘭𝘥 𝘯𝘰𝘵 𝘣𝘦 𝘥𝘦𝘱𝘭𝘰𝘺𝘦𝘥 𝘵𝘰 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘳𝘦𝘲𝘶𝘪𝘳𝘦𝘥 𝘱𝘭𝘢𝘵𝘧𝘰𝘳𝘮. 𝘕𝘰𝘸 𝘸𝘦’𝘳𝘦 𝘳𝘦𝘣𝘶𝘪𝘭𝘥𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘪𝘵.\n\n\nI see 𝘁𝘄𝗼 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗰𝗮𝘀𝗲𝘀 𝗹𝗶𝗸𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝘀 𝗲𝘃𝗲𝗿𝘆 𝘆𝗲𝗮𝗿.\nThree months of work — and no one checked whether the solution could be deployed at all.\nA simple Hello World deployed in week one would have saved them months.\n\nTechnical people naturally tend to focus mostly on the code; that’s what is expected of them. However, if you 𝗰𝗼𝗺𝗯𝗶𝗻𝗲 𝗲𝗻𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗲𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗸𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵 𝗮 𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗮𝗴𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗮𝗹 𝗼𝗻𝗲, the results will be strikingly better.\n\nLet me give an example.\nEarly in my career, Joel Spolsky influenced me a lot.\nHis radical question still matters: “Can you make deployment in one step?”\n\nHe believed deployment must be so automated that anyone can press a button and ship the product.\nThis forces you to build systems that make it impossible to deploy garbage 🗑️\n\nIt’s about 𝗳𝗮𝘀𝘁𝗲𝗿 𝗶𝘁𝗲𝗿𝗮𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻𝘀.\nAutomation shortens the path from idea → result → feedback.\nFast iterations are a managerial idea — about shortening the managerial cycle: the time from task to feedback. Here it is combined with an engineering process.\n\nAnd when you combine engineering + managerial thinking,\nyou become more valuable.\n💰 And that always converts into money: company profit and your salary.",
